      },
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest — normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) — is directly linked to the clinical endpoint of plasma-free hemoglobin accumulation rate, which is the regulatory acceptance criterion for VAD devices. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model translates local shear stress and exposure time to hemolysis probability, and the volume-integrated NIH is the scalar output compared against the clinical threshold. Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress magnitude distribution and Lagrangian blood element exposure time) are documented as mechanistic intermediate quantities providing diagnostic insight. The mapping from computational QoI to clinical endpoint is explicit and traceable, satisfying Gradation 4 relevance requirements."
