    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed at Model Risk Level 5 for a Class III VAD device. Achieved levels meet or exceed required levels for every factor: Software QA (4/4), Numerical Code Verification (4/4), Discretization Error (5/4), Test Conditions (4/3), Output Comparison (4/4), Relevance of QoI (4/4), Relevance of Validation Activities (4/4), Numerical Solver Error (4/3), Use Error (3/3), Model Form (4/4), Model Inputs (4/4), Test Samples (3/3), Equivalency of Input Parameters (4/4). Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification with 1000 samples was performed across 11 uncertain inputs; 95% CI on NIH is documented at all five operating points. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that the primary QoI (NIH) is most sensitive to the hemolysis model constant C (±18%) and blood viscosity (±11%), with all other inputs contributing less than ±8%. The mean absolute error on NIH across all validation points is 9.3%, within the 15% acceptance threshold, and prediction intervals overlap experimental uncertainty intervals at all five operating points. The provenance chain is complete from raw experimental data through CFD outputs to the credibility decision. No credibility gaps remain; the package is accepted for regulatory submission supporting the Class III VAD 510(k) or PMA pathway.",
